-- Agile vs Waterfall Methodologies (topic_id: 100028)
(100028,'Agile methodology is an iterative and incremental approach to software development that emphasizes flexibility, collaboration, and customer feedback.'                                                     , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Waterfall methodology is a traditional, linear approach to software development where each phase of the project is completed before moving on to the next.'                                                , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'In Agile, work is divided into small chunks called iterations or sprints, and the software is developed incrementally with frequent releases and updates.'                                                 , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Agile methodologies include Scrum, Kanban, and Extreme Programming (XP), each with its own approach to managing work and delivering software.'                                                             , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Waterfall is suitable for projects with well-defined requirements that are unlikely to change, such as those in regulated industries.'                                                                     , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Agile focuses on continuous improvement and customer collaboration, while Waterfall emphasizes following a predefined plan and meeting deadlines.'                                                         , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Agile allows for flexibility and adaptation during the development process, while Waterfall can be rigid and resistant to changes once the project is underway.'                                           , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
(100028,'Agile practices encourage frequent feedback and rapid delivery of small, incremental updates, while Waterfall delivers a complete product at the end of the project.'                                      , '2025-01-13 00:00'),
