-- Design Patterns in Software (topic_id: 100030)
(100030,'Design patterns are typical solutions to common problems in software design that can be reused across different projects.'                                                                                 , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030, 'There are three main categories of design patterns: creational, structural, and behavioral patterns.'                                                                                                     , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'Creational patterns provide solutions for object creation mechanisms, trying to create objects in a manner suitable to the situation.'                                                                     , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'Structural patterns deal with object composition, ensuring that the structure of objects or classes is flexible and efficient.'                                                                            , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'Behavioral patterns define the interactions between objects, helping them communicate and act in a way that enhances their interaction.'                                                                   , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it.'                                                                                             , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'The Factory Method pattern defines an interface for creating objects but allows subclasses to alter the type of created objects.'                                                                          , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'The Observer pattern allows a subject to notify its observers when there is a change in state, commonly used for event-driven programming.'                                                                , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100030,'Design patterns help developers avoid reinventing the wheel and promote best practices in code, making it more maintainable and understandable.'                                                           , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
