-- Effective Java Programming (topic_id: 100031)
(100031,'Effective Java is a set of programming best practices and guidelines for writing efficient, readable, and maintainable Java code.'                                                                         , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'One of the key practices in Effective Java is to use immutable objects where possible to ensure thread safety and simplify code.'                                                                          , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'Another recommendation is to favor composition over inheritance to reduce tight coupling and increase flexibility in code design.'                                                                         , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'Effective Java encourages using generics to write type-safe code that can be reused across different types and objects.'                                                                                   , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'The book stresses the importance of understanding the Java memory model, garbage collection, and performance optimization techniques.'                                                                     , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'Effective Java promotes proper handling of exceptions by favoring checked exceptions when appropriate and ensuring they are used to signal errors.'                                                        , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'The use of the builder pattern for constructing objects is recommended to create more readable and maintainable code when dealing with complex object creation.'                                           , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'The book emphasizes proper resource management by using try-with-resources for automatic resource cleanup to avoid resource leaks.'                                                                        , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100031,'Effective Java advises on optimizing code through profiling, understanding trade-offs, and using common Java utilities such as the Collections framework.'                                                 , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
