-- Database Indexing Strategies (topic_id: 100033)
(100033,'Database indexing is a technique used to optimize the performance of queries by creating data structures that improve data retrieval speed.'                                                               , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'Common types of database indexes include B-tree indexes, hash indexes, and full-text indexes.'                                                                                                            , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'B-tree indexes are widely used in relational databases and are best for equality and range queries.'                                                                                                      , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'Hash indexes are good for equality comparisons but perform poorly with range queries.'                                                                                                                    , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'Choosing the right index depends on the query patterns and the structure of the database.'                                                                                                                , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033,'Indexes can greatly speed up query performance, but they come with a trade-off in terms of disk space and slower writes.'                                                                                  , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033,'Composite indexes, which involve multiple columns, can be used to optimize queries that filter or sort based on multiple criteria.'                                                                        , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'Properly analyzing query execution plans can help in determining which indexes to create or remove.'                                                                                                      , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
(100033, 'Too many indexes can degrade performance, so careful index management and optimization are important.'                                                                                                    , '2025-01-14 00:00'),
