-- Concurrency in Java (topic_id: 100037)
(100037,'Concurrency in Java refers to the ability of the Java program to execute multiple tasks simultaneously, utilizing multiple processor cores efficiently.'                                                   , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Java provides several mechanisms for concurrency, such as threads, the Executor framework, and the Fork/Join framework.'                                                                                   , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Multithreading is the most common form of concurrency in Java, where multiple threads execute concurrently within the same program.'                                                                       , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'The `synchronized` keyword is used to ensure that only one thread can access a block of code at a time, preventing race conditions.'                                                                       , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'The Executor framework provides a higher-level replacement for the `Thread` class, simplifying thread management and task execution.'                                                                      , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Javas `java.util.concurrent` package contains powerful tools for managing concurrency, such as thread pools, atomic variables, and locks.'                                                                , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Deadlocks occur when two or more threads are blocked forever, waiting for each other to release resources. Java provides tools for avoiding and resolving deadlocks.'                                      , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'The Fork/Join framework helps to implement divide-and-conquer algorithms by breaking tasks into smaller tasks and executing them concurrently.'                                                            , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Concurrency can greatly improve performance by making better use of system resources, but it also introduces complexity in handling synchronization and communication.'                                    , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
(100037,'Java 8 introduced the `CompletableFuture` API, enabling asynchronous programming that allows non-blocking operations and combining multiple asynchronous tasks.'                                           , '2025-01-15 00:00'),
